>>114806679
>The music for this aria was not composed by Vivaldi. The aria, originally called Sposa, non mi conosci, was taken from the Geminiano Giacomelli's opera La Merope (1734), composed before Vivaldi's pasticcio Bajazet. It was a common practice during Vivaldi's time to compile arias from other composers with one own's work for an opera. Vivaldi himself composed the arias for the good characters and mostly used existing arias from other composers for the villains in this opera.

>melody

>textures

>emotion

Examples of disingenuous, contrived and pretentious reasons for appreciating music:
>the artistic or intellectual concepts and themes behind the music rather than the actual music itself
>the technical ability of the musician

posts.com:
Personally, I have to say that I never had much time for King Crimson. I disliked their first album and, apart from a track here and there, didn't find much I cared for on later albums either. To make things harder, they were contemporaries of Henry Cow and we were often pointlessly compared with them (especially Fred Frith who got foolishly compared/confused with Robert Fripp). But we never saw the connection really; they were working in a much narrower musical field than we were. And when they began to make big statements about their originality for improvising (around Jaimie Muir/Larks Tongues time) we found that frankly rather pathetic. But that was their way - after all Fripp claimed to have invented 'frippertronics', which is either a mark of ignorance on his part or outrageous arrogance, since every guitarist 'invented' that obvious procedure. I was not a fan of the other groups you list either, or Yes or Genesis for that matter, the quintessential 'progressive' groups. I don't think we had much in common with any of them. We certainly didn't learn anything from them. I, for instance, would have to go back to early Zappa, Beefheart, Barrett's Pink Floyd, Soft Machine, AMM, Sun Ra, Coltrane, Coleman, Stockhausen, Schoenberg and so on for influences. And for contemporary bands in the 70's, Magma, Faust, Samla Mammas Manna.

-Chris Cutler

Probably because the committee always overreacts to criticism from inducted musicians and online and the next year of nominees they pick are a reaction to that.
A few years ago they were getting shit from some inductees and online sites about the lack of women in the hall, so the last 3 years they started getting through the backlog of obvious acts to put in. Then last year they got intense criticism for straying too far from rock, namely with Duran Duran being the closest inductee to actual rock and Judas Priest being forced in the side category. Dolly Pardon trying to bow out because she thought she was taking a spot from a rock artist (and even now trying to make a rock album to "justify" her being in despite everyone thinking she's influential enough to be in anyway) sealed the deal.
So now we got a number of considered huge rock snubs (Zevon, Soundgarden, Iron Maiden, Joy Division) along with White Stripes to guarantee at least one gets in this time, if not multiple

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Listened to pic related

Overall impression is that they're a competent stoner/psych/doom band (basically stoner but with some of the poppier Uncle Acid style - I can hear some QOTSA influence too I think) but they're a bit like Acid Mammoth in that they're playing all the right stuff but are kind of boring.

Elements in their favour are that their bass player is quite strong and has an interesting tone during the mini solos in 'All is Fine', though that song in particular runs out of steam half way through. The songs in general could be trimmed a bit imo, I'm not sure why 5-8mins is so normal for this genre - if you want people to groove you need to keep it tight.

'Electric Traveller', one of two singles from the album, starts strong but falls victim to this issue Aawks seem to have where they run out of gas mid-song and the groove grinds to a halt, then chugs along at half the pace for no reason. It does this weird tempo change a few times, kind of like the band had a few different ideas and duct-taped them together rather than making it sound coherent.

'Space City', the other single, is a bit tighter and has an interesting chorus with slightly dissonant vocals, but despite a relatively stable tempo it still sounds a bit disjointed and doesn't really spark much interest.

It's hard to put my finger on why I don't care for it exactly, it just sounds kind of stock and uninspired overall. It's like if I got an AI to generate a stoner/psych sound it would come out with this, in the same way that if I asked it to make generic stoner metal it would produce Acid Mammoth. By the end of the album it's hard to remember any song in particular, it all blends together because the overall sound is pretty uniform despite sections not always fitting together neatly.

It has a lot of the right elements for this type of music but is missing that secret ingredient that gets you hooked on the sound.

Kid A predicted 9/11
>The first song on Kid A paints the Manhattan skyline at 8:00 A.M. on Tuesday morning; the song is titled "Everything in Its Right Place." People woke up that day "sucking on a lemon," because that's what life normally feels like on the Manhattan subway; the city is a beautiful, sour, sarcastic place. We soon move onto song two, which is the title track. It is the sound of woozy, ephemeral normalcy. It is the sound of Jonny Greenwood playing an Ondes Martenot, an instrument best remembered for its use in the Star Trek theme song. You can imagine humans walking to work, riding elevators, getting off the C train and the 3 train, and thinking about a future that will be a lot like the present, only better. The term KID A is Yorke's moniker for the first cloned human, which he (only half jokingly) suspects may already exist. The consciously misguided message is this: Science is the answer. Technology solves everything, because technology is invulnerable. And this is what almost everyone in America thought around 8:30 A.M. But something happens three and a half minutes into "Kid A". It suddenly doesn't feel right, and you don't exactly know why. This is followed by track three, "The National Anthem"

This is when the first plane slams into the north tower at 470 mph.

"The National Anthem" sounds a bit like a Morphine song. It's a completley different direction from the first two songs on KID A, and it's confusing; it's chaotic. "What's going on?," the lyrics ask. "What's going on?" It gets crazier and crazier, until the second plane hits the second tower (at 9:03 A.M. in reality and at 3:42 in the song). For a moment, things are somber. But then it gets more anarchic. Which leads into track four, "How to Disappear Completely." This is the point where it feels like the world is possibly ending. People try to convince themselves that they are not there. People keep repeating: "This isn't happening". People are "floating" (read: falling) to the earth.

It's never too late. The question is how good you are right now.

Because you have to be at least as good as the average pro-performer in your chosen genre who isn't a drug dealer, a prostitute, a nepobaby, or otherwise independently wealthy before you attempt such a foolish chosen career path. And if you're not already keyed into your local scene, you will be shocked at how good their best musicians are:

https://youtu.be/RKuCjPYGAHw

That guy's amazing. He's not nationally famous, but he's still a pro, full-time bluesman in my scene.

And keep in mind, this isn't the 20th Century anymore. There's way less jobs for pro-musicians than there was then, but making music your sidegig doesn't have to be nearly as big a handicap as it was.

Besides, top-level musicians have kept their dayjobs until the time was right since forever. Wes Montgomery had dayjons until he was in his mid-30s, and I guarantee you're not as good at anything now as he was at jazz guitar:

https://youtu.be/PbGGP_YGAi4

Granted, Wes had a wife, seven kids, and assuredly smoked quite a bit of tobacco to keep alert for such a brutal schedule. But I'm pretty sure you have none of those obligations yourself, neither.

if you wanna transition you could either do it smooth by crossfading your new loops in and matching their timing, hiding the fade behind other samples or melody if it sounds weird, or you could do a hard transition/breakdown where you abruptly cut/filter/downpitch/however you wanna end your first loop, pause, then start the next loop. posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114814494
>Record left and right channel separately.

Doesn't work all that well. Stereo by definition will have differing signals on the left and right channels and a compressor (even with untouched exactly the same settings for both recordings) will react slightly differently to them, resulting in the stereo image wandering at times when the signal differs between left and right most.

Stereo or two-channel compressors have a "Link" function where the compressor can be set to react exactly the same for both left and right, avoiding that issue.

>Midwest emo (or Midwestern emo[1]) refers to the emo scene and/or subgenre[2] that developed in 1990s Midwestern United States. Employing unconventional vocal stylings, distinct guitar riffs and arpeggiated melodies,[3] Midwest emo bands shifted away from the genre's hardcore punk roots and drew on indie rock and math rock approaches.[4] According to the author and critic Andy Greenwald, "this was the period when emo earned many, if not all, of the stereotypes that have lasted to this day: boy-driven, glasses-wearing, overly sensitive, overly brainy, chiming-guitar-driven college music."[5] Midwest emo is sometimes used interchangeably with "second-wave emo".[6] Although implied by the name, Midwest emo does not solely refer to bands and artists from the Midwestern United States, and the style is played by outfits across the United States and internationally.[7]

https://secondhandsongs.com/work/10913/versions

Another standard recorded by many but mostly associated with the Flamingos' 1959 top 10 hit version. As you may notice, Frank Sinatra covered it. Doris Day also covered it, backed by...Axel Stordahl who to his credit doesn't just copypaste the arrangement from the Sinatra recording. That was from a movie soundtrack and not a standalone single. Her singing is a little deadbeat though. Patti Page covered it a little later but the slow weepy string gush of all these versions make you understand why the Flamingos' "I Only Have Eyes For You" is the one everyone remembers today.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114823908
It's actually much worse.
The sample Ashcroft took was not even from the Stones song, it was from a cover done by an orchestra.

So the whole authorship claim was indirectly linked to the Stones. He didn't just chop up a part from a Stones song. He sampled a cover that used the melodic line from a Stones song.

And since the Stone's manager was some Jewish guy, he never agreed to give them a license to use it. So he sued the Verve and got all the royalty rights from Ashcroft.

After the Jewish Stones manager died, the Stones themselves agreed to give Ashcroft his rights back.

Can /mu/ help me find some song that I listened to a lot when I was around 11 years old that I haven't been able to find since? This was from back when myspace was still popular. I have searched for it multiple times and I have never once been able to find it.

Here is everything I know about the song. It was metal, probably nu-metal, maybe not entirely but it at least took influence from that. I stumbled across this myspace page, I think it was for the band, and it was one of the songs in their page's playlist. I believe the band was french, or at least spoke french, but the song itself was totally in english. I think it was around 4 minutes long. I remember one part of the lyrics VERY vividly, and that is usually what I search for, but evidently the band is not popular enough to be in most lyric website's databases. I did search a bit on the metal-archives, and didn't find it, but I also didn't pick through every single result as it seems it is pretty liberal in the songs it matches with.

As far as I know this might be an insanely underground band that practically no one listened to, which is why I can't find it, but from what I remember the production quality on the song was pretty high, it wasn't some lofi indie sounding shit, but rather it sounded like it came from an actual studio of some sorts. I know the myspace page at the time was also promoting some book which was about demons and shit, but Im pretty sure it was a fiction story and not some occult manuscript or something. I think possibly a comedy but I was like 11 so I don't entirely trust that I have a good understanding of it just from reading the synopsis. I also remember that the main color on the myspace page was red, I think the background for it was red, perhaps just that solid color.

CONT (wish 4chan just told me how many characters too long my post is instead of twice rejecting it)

I think it even went right into a guitar solo there but again I am not certain.
>Without warning,
>Like a plane crash,
>I am the passenger...
>In black, MOURNING
When the vocalist say's mourning it has sort of turned into a shout.

If you play piano long enough, you'll learn how to play it.
The thing with Beefheart is that he was an improviser. He couldn't arrange, or play something over and over, and he had a short attention span, which is why when he recorded just bits and pieces of music he needed his band members to sort them out, but when he plunked out something from start to finish is when he was at his best. There is a good and a bad side to his approach.


>Richard Redus: I became cynical about the music as I watched it being created, because I started to realize that it wasn’t a grand thought-out or even a grand un-thought-out musical thunderbolt. It was just this kind of pieced-together hodge-podge of notes that half came from the band members, half came from Don. But as I saw the process where he would whistle something then he would kind of bully the player to play it and then the player might throw in his own rhythm and Don would then claim credit for doing it himself. That’s how the pieces kind of grew, and at the time I felt disillusioned by that. I had imagined Don as being a guy who would just, with his great genius, make up the parts on the piano and hand them to you and you play them.

Here's some info on the polymetrical aspect of the album. No wonder that TMR was arranged by the drummer, he was deep into this and his fingerprints are all over the rhythms of the album.
>If I am playing a part three beats long, and you’re playing a part 4 beats long, then I’m starting my second “one” on your “four,” my third one your “three,” and so on. In order for us to end at the same time, we must do a number of beats that has a common denominator. For instance, 3 and 4 both divide into 12 equally and so every 12 beats, there is a “touch-point” as I referred to it or the end of a cycle and the beginning of another. If you’re listening to the other player as is common to do in music, it’s really easy to get confused and start altering your part. For instance, if Bill said, “I like dogs” at the same time and in the same tempo Jeff said “I like dogs too,” it would look like this:

>Bill: I like dogs I like dogs I like dogs I like dogs I …
Jeff: I like dogs too I like dogs Too I like dogs too I…
If you look closely, you’ll see that the top line says it’s part four times, but the bottom part, because it is longer, only says it three times in order to wind up at the same place in time. The last “I” is the first I of the second set of parts. The cycle is completed just before this point.
This can be further complicated by adding a bass part in five…I like dogs too much!

>Bill: I like dogs I like dogs I like dogs I like dogs I
Jeff: I like dogs too I like dogs too I like dogs too I
Mark: I like dogs too much I like dogs too much I like dogs..

>As you can see, Mark’s part, “I like dogs too much” is incomplete the last time as he still needs to say “too much,’ which means he either has to stop after his third “dogs” or the other guys need to keep talking for a while.

>>114820499
I don't think it's necessarily a board culture thing, if anything it's a shift in music, internet and attention economies. back then 4chan could exist in a more vastly dispersed internet, alongside a wide array of miscellaneous niche websites. Information was difficult to agregate so in many ways this place became an unofficial hub that was convenient to anonymously exist in. what became novel on this board could thus carry more weight and influence the general internet consesnus. nowadays, anonimity is no longer the norm, music discovery is easier than ever, and information/internet traffic is more centralized than ever. whatever reach we had, is no longer possible. if anything we're lucky that we're not as slow as other blue boards. there's still novelty to this place but we're well past a heyday that will likely never come back

My understanding is that the SQ64 has three polyphonic tracks, and one drum track that can send midi information.

When I do runs on the treadmill, I warm up by walking for max 5 minutes, then I start at a pace that is intentionally too fast to maintain. Once I can't handle it anymore and I feel like I'm going to die, I slow the treadmill down .5 kilometers per hour and keep going. Every time I slow it down, I feel like absolute shit for about a minute or two until my body gets comfortable at this pace, and then a few minutes later I feel like death again, so I slow down.
You'd be surprised how much you're actually able to do if you just allow your body to stay in the "quitting" zone. It's way more difficult than going back to walking, but if you can just hang on a little bit longer you'll get the most amazing runner's high.
